nging Liberalism Schwartzman explores the reasons why concepts such as rights and equality can sometimes reinforce oppression. She argues that certain forms of abstraction and individualism are central to liberal methodology and that these give rise to a number of problems. Drawing on the work of feminist moral, political, and legal theorists, she constructs an approach that employs these concepts, while viewing them from within a critique of social relations of power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271030296zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271030296423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271030296.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK